Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ludlow, Shropshire, England":"Ludlow, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1210–about 1270":"1210–about 1270","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1180–1230":"1180–1230","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1165–1230":"1165–1230","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","about 1270":"about 1270","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","about 1240":"about 1240","1170":"1170","about 1230":"about 1230","1180":"1180","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Ludlow, Shropshire Unitary Authority, Shropshire, England":"Warminster, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Ludlow, Shropshire, England":"Ludlow, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swineton,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and Nottinghamshire) and Scottish (Fife): habitational name from any of various places called Swinton, for example in Berwickshire, North Yorkshire, Yorkshire, and Lancashire. The Lancashire, North Yorkshire, and Yorkshire placenames derive from Old English <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, pig’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Berwickshire placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Sveinn</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Swinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and Nottinghamshire) and Scottish (Fife): habitational name from any of various places called Swinton, for example in Berwickshire, North Yorkshire, Yorkshire, and Lancashire. The Lancashire, North Yorkshire, and Yorkshire placenames derive from Old English <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, pig’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Berwickshire placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Sveinn</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Petronilla","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old female name; an Italian diminutive formed from Pietro, i.e. Peter."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Petronilla Swineton, de Swinton was born in 1210, in Hill Deverill, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Norman de Swineton Feudal Lord of Ludelawe Castle, was 45 and her mother, Mrs. Norman de Swineton, was 41. She had at least 1 son with Matthew LUDLOW, de Ludlowe, Ludlow. She died about 1270, in Warminster, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1210–about 1270":"1210–umbes 1270","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1180–1230":"1180–1230","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1165–1230":"1165–1230","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1170":"1170","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1180":"1180","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Ludlow, Shropshire Unitary Authority, Shropshire, England":"Warminster, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ludlow, Shropshire, England":"Ludlow, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1210–about 1270":"1210–noin 1270","1210–1270":"1210–1270","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1180–1230":"1180–1230","1240–1300":"1240–1300",